</div>

<div class="evidence" id="win051">
<h3>WIN-051: Tidal N2 period</h3>
<p><strong>Claim:</strong> Tidal N2 period matches dome model.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> N2 (12.66 hours) is a semi-diurnal lunar constituent caused by the moon's elliptical orbit (varying distance). On the globe, N2's amplitude depends on the moon's eccentricity and distance. The dome places the moon at ~2,534 km with no stated orbital eccentricity. N2 specifically arises from the moon's elliptical orbit (eccentricity e ≈ 0.055); without a published eccentricity parameter, the dome model cannot derive N2's amplitude or phase from first principles — it can only retrodict the period from global tidal observations. The same pattern problem applies: at 2,534 km altitude above a 20,015 km disc, the tidal force is sharply concentrated beneath the moon and negligible across most of the disc. There is no far-side bulge. Real tides show two high tides per lunar day everywhere — a pattern that requires the moon to be far enough away that tidal force is nearly uniform across the planet. The author has never published a tidal amplitude or spatial pattern calculation using dome geometry. See <a href="#part4b" onclick="showTab('selftest');return false">Section 4.5.2</a> and <a href="https://doi.org/10.1098/rspa.1921.0088">Doodson (1921)</a>.</p>
<p><span class="verdict-tag vt-selfcon">SELF-CONTRADICTED</span> Period is trivial. Dome's local moon produces a sharp localized spike, not the observed global two-bulge pattern.</p>
