</div>

<div class="evidence" id="win015">
<h3>WIN-015: Meyl scalar Faraday</h3>
<p><strong>Claim:</strong> Klaus Meyl&#39;s proposed &quot;scalar waves&quot; penetrate a Faraday cage, violating standard electromagnetism.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> Published only in non-peer-reviewed conference proceedings. Independent replication attempts consistently explain Meyl's results via classical near-field (evanescent) coupling: at short distances (< λ/2π), electromagnetic energy leaks through cabinet seams, cable feedthroughs, or finite cage conductivity without invoking scalar waves — a well-understood effect in antenna near-field theory that fully accounts for observed apparent penetration.</p>
<p><span class="verdict-tag vt-notdemo">NOT DEMONSTRATED</span> No peer-reviewed replication. Near-field evanescent coupling (standard antenna theory) fully explains Meyl's results. Thousands of precision experiments globally rely on standard Faraday shielding with no anomalous penetration observed.</p>
