<div class="evidence" id="win058">
<h3>WIN-058: The 0.9941 EW scale factor can be compared to the globe&#39;s flattening f = 1/298.257 to illustrate the epistemological difference: the globe&#39;s flattening is derived from Earth&#39;s rotation rate and mass distribution, independently confirmed by four methods (satellite orbit perturbations, gravimetry, VLBI, SLR) each giving consistent results. The dome&#39;s 0.9941 is the output of a least-squares minimization on six WGS84-derived route distances — no physical derivation, no independent confirmation, no prior prediction. The dome&#39;s own AI context page lists &#39;EW scale 0.9941 physical interpretation&#39; as an open question, conceding the parameter has no theoretical basis. A genuine dome-derived prediction would compute 0.9941 from disc radius (20,015 km), firmament height (9,086 km), or aetheric wave speed before comparing to city distances; instead, 0.9941 was reverse-engineered from WGS84 data and then claimed as a prediction.Unified angular coordinate</h3>
<p><strong>Claim:</strong> Dome&#39;s unified angular coordinate system with scale factor 0.9941 reduces cross-equatorial distance errors within the dome&#39;s own V13 framework.</p>
<p><strong>Evidence:</strong> WIN-058 is listed on the dome's wins page with a one-line claim but no supporting equations, derivation, measurements, or physical mechanism — it is effectively undefined on the dome's own site. The dome provides no detailed description of what 'unified angular coordinate' means: no formula derivation, no geometric basis from dome parameters, and no specification of what physical quantity it represents. Before evaluating a claim, the claim must be defined; WIN-058 fails this threshold. Unlike WIN-057 (which at least describes the two-zone topology), WIN-058 provides no justifying content: no formula for the 0.9941 scale factor, no geometric derivation from disc radius or firmament height, and no specification of what physical quantity the 'unified angular coordinate' represents. The unified angular coordinate with scale factor 0.9941 was not derived a priori from dome geometry — it was fitted post-hoc to match WGS84 geodetic distances on six known routes. Any free parameter fitted to known data will reduce residuals; the question is whether 0.9941 was predicted before measuring. The dome's own AI context lists 'EW scale 0.9941 physical interpretation' as an open question — conceding the parameter has no theoretical basis. No prospective prediction states: 'Dome geometry predicts EW angular scale = 0.9941'; instead, the value was selected to minimize residuals when comparing dome coordinates to WGS84 distances. This is retrodiction (fitting known data), not prediction (forecasting new data). WGS84's flattening parameter (1/298.257) is derived from satellite orbit perturbations and independently confirmed by GPS, VLBI, and SLR to sub-millimeter precision — it is a measured physical quantity with a derivation from rotational physics. The dome's 0.9941 has no independent confirmation, no derivation from dome physics, and no prospective test. Furthermore, the V13 coordinate system still requires WGS84 distances as input (see the model's own OPEN-001 and OPEN-003 acknowledgments), making it dependent on globe geodesy rather than independent of it. Why 0.9941 specifically? The dome provides no derivation from disc radius (20,015 km), firmament height (9,086 km), aetheric wave speed, or any other dome parameter — only the fitted result. The value minimizes residuals on six WGS84-derived routes, making it a least-squares output, not a theoretical prediction. A genuine dome-derived prediction would compute 0.9941 from the disc's geometry before comparing to city distances; instead, 0.9941 was reverse-engineered from WGS84 data. For comparison, the globe's flattening f = 1/298.257 follows from Earth's rotation rate and mass distribution and is confirmed by four independent methods (satellite orbits, gravimetry, VLBI, SLR). The dome's 0.9941 has zero independent confirmations and remains an 'open question' on the dome's own AI context page. Standard geodesy achieves sub-0.01% distance accuracy worldwide using the WGS84 ellipsoid with two global parameters derived from rotational physics (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-662-03482-5">Torge & Müller, 2012</a>). The dome's unified angular coordinate achieves ~5–7% accuracy with multiple fitted parameters — more parameters producing less accuracy. The dome's 6.2% RMSE is 600× worse than Vincenty geodesy even after fitting a free parameter to known routes, and the dome's coordinate system still cannot handle equatorial routes at all (the dome's own OPEN-015 concedes near-equatorial cities 'fall beyond the range' of the model).</p>
<p><span class="verdict-tag vt-notdemo">NOT DEMONSTRATED</span> The 0.9941 scale factor is a post-hoc fit to WGS84 distances, not a prediction derived from dome geometry. Any model with a free parameter can reduce residuals on known data; this is curve-fitting, not prediction.</p>
